    "is_good_patch": true,
    "synth_pr": "\n## Title: Fix byte ordering in NFAPI message packing/unpacking functions\n\n### Summary\nThe NFAPI library had incorrect byte ordering implementations in the push/pull functions for little-endian systems. This caused all packed data to have incorrect byte ordering, leading to unexpected behavior when calling functions like `pack_nmm_stop_response()`.\n\nThe issue was in the `#else` branches of the byte ordering functions which were incorrectly implementing big-endian byte ordering instead of little-endian byte ordering.\n\n### Changes\n- `nfapi/open-nFAPI/nfapi/src/nfapi.c`: Fixed byte ordering in push/pull functions for 16-bit and 32-bit integers (signed and unsigned)\n\n### Reproduction\nWhen calling `pack_nmm_stop_response()` on a little-endian system, the `error_code` field would be packed with incorrect byte ordering. This would cause the unpacked value to be different from the original value, leading to unexpected behavior in the application.\n\nThe issue can be observed by:\n1. Creating an `nfapi_nmm_stop_response_t` structure with a specific `error_code` value\n2. Calling `nfapi_p4_message_pack()` to pack the structure\n3. Calling `nfapi_p4_message_unpack()` to unpack the packed data\n4. Comparing the original `error_code` with the unpacked `error_code` - they would not match on little-endian systems\n\nAfter this fix, the packed and unpacked values should match correctly.\n"
}